1
00:00:30,615 --> 00:00:33,733
<i>It's an important and popular fact</i>

2
00:00:33,785 --> 00:00:37,653
<i>that things are not always
what they seem.</i>

3
00:00:37,747 --> 00:00:41,365
<i>For instance, on the planet Earth,
man had always assumed</i>

4
00:00:41,459 --> 00:00:45,293
<i>that he was the most intelligent
species occupying the planet,</i>

5
00:00:45,338 --> 00:00:48,046
<i>instead of the third most intelligent.</i>

6
00:00:48,133 --> 00:00:52,627
<i>The second most intelligent creatures
were dolphins, who, curiously enough,</i>

7
00:00:52,679 --> 00:00:56,638
<i>had long known of the impending
destruction of the planet Earth.</i>

8
00:00:56,683 --> 00:00:59,015
<i>They'd made many attempts
to alert mankind,</i>

9
00:00:59,144 --> 00:01:02,136
<i>but most of their communications
were misinterpreted</i>

10
00:01:02,188 --> 00:01:05,681
<i>as amusing attempts to punch footballs
or whistle for titbits.</i>

11
00:01:05,817 --> 00:01:10,277
<i>So they eventually decided they would
leave Earth by their own means.</i>

12
00:01:10,321 --> 00:01:13,564
<i>The last ever dolphin message
was misinterpreted</i>

13
00:01:13,658 --> 00:01:16,867
<i>as a sophisticated attempt
to do a backward somersault</i>

14
00:01:16,995 --> 00:01:19,987
through a hoop,
<i>whistling</i> The Star-Spangled Banner.

15
00:01:20,123 --> 00:01:21,830
<i>In fact, the message was this:</i>

16
00:01:21,958 --> 00:01:24,825
<i>"So long and thanks for all the fish."</i>

17
00:01:51,488 --> 00:01:53,525
<i>So long and thanks for all the fish</i>

18
00:01:53,656 --> 00:01:55,613
<i>So sad that it should come to this</i>

19
00:01:55,700 --> 00:01:59,819
<i>We tried to warn you all but, oh, dear</i>

20
00:01:59,871 --> 00:02:01,953
<i>You may not share our intellect</i>

21
00:02:02,040 --> 00:02:04,156
<i>Which might explain your disrespect</i>

22
00:02:04,209 --> 00:02:08,328
<i>For all the natural wonders
that grow around you</i>

23
00:02:08,379 --> 00:02:12,748
<i>So long, so long and thanks
for all the fish</i>

24
00:02:14,886 --> 00:02:16,797
<i>Your world's about to be destroyed</i>

25
00:02:16,888 --> 00:02:19,004
<i>There's no point getting all annoyed</i>

26
00:02:19,057 --> 00:02:23,551
<i>Lie back and let the planet
dissolve around you</i>

27
00:02:23,645 --> 00:02:25,556
<i>Despite those nets of tuna fleets</i>

28
00:02:25,647 --> 00:02:27,638
<i>We thought that most of you were sweet</i>

29
00:02:27,732 --> 00:02:31,817
<i>Especially tiny tots
and your pregnant women</i>

30
00:02:31,903 --> 00:02:34,065
<i>So long, so long
so long, so long, so long</i>

31
00:02:34,155 --> 00:02:36,317
<i>So long, so long
so long, so long, so long</i>

32
00:02:36,407 --> 00:02:40,401
<i>So long, so long
and thanks for all the fish</i>

33
00:02:42,747 --> 00:02:46,957
<i>If I had just one last wish</i>

34
00:02:47,043 --> 00:02:51,128
<i>I would like a tasty fish</i>

35
00:02:51,214 --> 00:02:55,503
<i>If we could just change one thing</i>

36
00:02:55,593 --> 00:02:59,757
<i>We would all have learned to sing</i>

37
00:02:59,931 --> 00:03:03,970
<i>Come one and all</i>

38
00:03:04,102 --> 00:03:08,187
<i>Man and mammal</i>

39
00:03:08,273 --> 00:03:11,641
<i>Side by side</i>

40
00:03:11,734 --> 00:03:17,730
<i>In life's great gene pool</i>

41
00:03:36,801 --> 00:03:39,008
<i>So long, so long
so long, so long, so long</i>

42
00:03:39,095 --> 00:03:41,177
<i>So long, so long
so long, so long, so long</i>

43
00:03:41,264 --> 00:03:47,226
<i>So long, so long
and thanks for all the fish</i>

44
00:04:00,742 --> 00:04:05,077
The extraordinary <i>story</i>
of The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy

45
00:04:05,163 --> 00:04:06,824
<i>begins very simply.</i>

46
00:04:06,915 --> 00:04:09,828
<i>It begins with a man.</i>

47
00:04:18,843 --> 00:04:22,507
<i>An Earthman, to be precise,
who no more knows his destiny,</i>

48
00:04:22,597 --> 00:04:26,090
<i>than a tea leaf knows the history
of the East India Company.</i>

49
00:04:28,394 --> 00:04:31,182
<i>His name is Arthur Dent.</i>

50
00:04:31,272 --> 00:04:34,560
<i>He is a five-foot-eight-inch-tall
ape descendant,</i>

51
00:04:34,692 --> 00:04:38,686
<i>and someone is trying to drive
a bypass through his house.</i>

52
00:04:43,993 --> 00:04:45,984
What do I want you to do about it?

53
00:04:46,037 --> 00:04:50,201
Find him and tell him I'm currently
lying flat on my back in front of...

54
00:04:50,291 --> 00:04:51,577
Fine, I'll hold.

55
00:04:51,709 --> 00:04:54,371
You can't lie in front
of the bulldozers forever.

56
00:04:54,462 --> 00:04:56,578
I'm game. We'll see who rusts first.

57
00:04:56,714 --> 00:05:00,002
This bypass has got to be built
and it is going to be built.

58
00:05:00,093 --> 00:05:04,132
- Why has it got to be built?
- It's a bypass.

59
00:05:04,222 --> 00:05:08,762
You've got to build bypasses. Besides,
you should've protested months ago.

60
00:05:08,893 --> 00:05:12,261
The plans have been on display
at the planning office for a year.

61
00:05:12,355 --> 00:05:15,017
On display?
I had to go down to a cellar.

62
00:05:15,149 --> 00:05:20,485
Mr Dent, have you any idea how much
damage this bulldozer would suffer

63
00:05:20,571 --> 00:05:23,029
if I just let it roll straight over you?

64
00:05:24,242 --> 00:05:27,234
- How much?
- None at all.

65
00:05:27,286 --> 00:05:30,119
<i>By a strange coincidence,
"none at all"</i>

66
00:05:30,206 --> 00:05:33,915
<i>is exactly how much suspicion
ape-descendant Arthur Dent had</i>

67
00:05:34,002 --> 00:05:35,993
<i>that one of his closest friends</i>

68
00:05:36,087 --> 00:05:39,580
<i>was not descended from an ape,
but was, in fact, from a small planet</i>

69
00:05:39,632 --> 00:05:42,966
<i>somewhere in the vicinity of Betelgeuse.</i>

70
00:05:43,761 --> 00:05:46,253
Arthur.

71
00:05:46,347 --> 00:05:48,133
- Ford.
- Yes?

72
00:05:48,224 --> 00:05:49,680
Here.

73
00:05:49,767 --> 00:05:51,144
There you are.

74
00:05:51,227 --> 00:05:53,059
Eat, drink. We gotta talk.

75
00:05:53,104 --> 00:05:56,347
Now's not the best time.
They're going to demolish my home.

76
00:05:57,942 --> 00:06:00,855
You already know? How?

77
00:06:00,945 --> 00:06:02,856
What do you...?

78
00:06:04,615 --> 00:06:07,744
Oh, they, they? When you say
"they" you mean they? Got it.

79
00:06:07,785 --> 00:06:12,495
Listen. I got somethin' important
I gotta tell you. Right now.

80
00:06:12,582 --> 00:06:15,040
Well, what about my house?

81
00:06:19,547 --> 00:06:25,042
Workers of the Earth, I bring
good tidings of peanuts and beer.

82
00:06:35,605 --> 00:06:37,437
Good. Let's go to the pub.

83
00:06:37,482 --> 00:06:40,474
They won't demolish it
until they've finished the beers.

84
00:06:40,610 --> 00:06:42,977
- Can we trust 'em?
- To the end of the Earth.

85
00:06:43,154 --> 00:06:45,486
- How far's that?
- About 12 minutes away.

86
00:06:46,699 --> 00:06:50,693
Barman, six pints of bitter and quickly.
The world's about to end.

87
00:06:50,787 --> 00:06:52,653
Six pints coming up.

88
00:06:52,789 --> 00:06:56,453
Keep the change.
You got about ten minutes to spend it.

89
00:06:56,542 --> 00:06:59,876
Three pints each? At lunchtime?

90
00:07:06,969 --> 00:07:09,006
Sorry.

91
00:07:09,055 --> 00:07:11,467
Time is an illusion.

92
00:07:11,516 --> 00:07:13,678
Lunchtime, doubly so.

93
00:07:13,768 --> 00:07:17,602
And eat those peanuts
because you'll need the salt.

94
00:07:17,688 --> 00:07:20,350
- Look, what is going on, Ford?
- Arthur...

95
00:07:22,485 --> 00:07:25,978
What if I told you
I really wasn't from Guildford?

96
00:07:26,030 --> 00:07:30,445
I was from a small planet
somewhere in the vicinity of Betelgeuse?

97
00:07:30,535 --> 00:07:34,073
- Is it something you're likely to say?
- Remember when we met?

98
00:07:41,087 --> 00:07:42,248
Out the way.

99
00:07:45,925 --> 00:07:46,915
Hi.

100
00:07:47,009 --> 00:07:50,047
Wasn't it strange I was trying
to shake hands with a car?

101
00:07:50,096 --> 00:07:51,678
I assumed you were drunk.

102
00:07:51,764 --> 00:07:55,849
I thought cars were the dominant
life form. I was introducing myself.

103
00:07:55,935 --> 00:08:00,395
You saved my life.
And now I'm saving yours. Please drink.

104
00:08:00,439 --> 00:08:03,773
It must be Thursday. I could never
get the hang of Thursdays.

105
00:08:03,901 --> 00:08:07,235
- If this is about your house...
- No, it's not about the house.

106
00:08:11,242 --> 00:08:13,358
- Who's he?
- She.

107
00:08:13,411 --> 00:08:17,075
Tricia McMillan.
We met at a fancy-dress party.

108
00:08:18,499 --> 00:08:20,581
<i>I hate those kind of parties.</i>

109
00:08:20,710 --> 00:08:23,577
<i>I'd rather have stayed at home
and ironed my hankies.</i>

110
00:08:23,671 --> 00:08:25,833
<i>- But there I was.</i>
- <i>Who are</i> you?

111
00:08:25,923 --> 00:08:27,664
<i>And there she was.</i>

112
00:08:27,758 --> 00:08:32,468
- Dent. Arthur Dent.
- No. I mean, who are you?

113
00:08:32,555 --> 00:08:35,798
Oh, the costume? Right.
"Livingstone, I presume."

114
00:08:36,934 --> 00:08:41,303
Yeah, it's not as clever as Darwin,
but the best I could do at short notice.

115
00:08:41,397 --> 00:08:43,434
You're the first to get that right.

116
00:08:43,524 --> 00:08:46,312
- Really?
- Yes. Everyone calls me Santa.

117
00:08:46,402 --> 00:08:48,939
- Right.
- I thought the beagle was a giveaway.

118
00:08:49,030 --> 00:08:50,646
So did I.

119
00:08:50,740 --> 00:08:53,152
People at these parties
are drunken idiots.

120
00:08:53,242 --> 00:08:54,653
What?

121
00:08:54,744 --> 00:08:57,361
All these people are idiots. God.

122
00:09:01,167 --> 00:09:02,908
That's awkward.

123
00:09:02,960 --> 00:09:04,792
Tell me.

124
00:09:06,672 --> 00:09:09,460
She was amazing though, Ford.

125
00:09:09,550 --> 00:09:12,542
<i>Beautiful, witty, mad as a balloon.</i>

126
00:09:12,637 --> 00:09:17,256
Without the beard,
you look at least 80 years younger.

127
00:09:17,350 --> 00:09:20,092
Maybe I'm de-evolving.

128
00:09:22,897 --> 00:09:28,563
Well, I should tell you that I do not
date single-celled organisms, OK?

129
00:09:31,280 --> 00:09:33,487
Let's go somewhere.

130
00:09:33,532 --> 00:09:37,696
Yeah. Definitely.
Where do you have in mind?

131
00:09:37,787 --> 00:09:41,746
- Madagascar.
- Is that that new club on Dean Street?

132
00:09:41,832 --> 00:09:45,166
No, it's a country
off the coast of Africa.

133
00:09:45,253 --> 00:09:48,211
That Madagascar?
Why are we waiting here?

134
00:09:48,839 --> 00:09:51,331
Wait a sec.

135
00:09:51,425 --> 00:09:53,007
Go.

136
00:09:56,138 --> 00:10:00,632
God, you're serious.
I can't go to Madagascar.

137
00:10:00,685 --> 00:10:03,768
- Why not?
- Because, I just, you know...

138
00:10:03,854 --> 00:10:05,231
- You're serious?
- Yeah.

139
00:10:05,314 --> 00:10:08,978
I want to go somewhere I've never been
and I'd like to go with you,

140
00:10:09,026 --> 00:10:11,734
so what do you say, Dr Livingstone?

141
00:10:12,905 --> 00:10:17,695
I say that's
an extraordinary proposition.

142
00:10:17,785 --> 00:10:20,777
I can't go. I mean, I've got a job.

143
00:10:20,871 --> 00:10:23,124
Quit. Get a new one
when you come back.

144
00:10:23,207 --> 00:10:25,198
I don't even know your real name.

145
00:10:25,334 --> 00:10:28,668
- Tricia McMillan.
- Well, Tricia McMillan.

146
00:10:29,630 --> 00:10:32,167
I have a proposition for you.

147
00:10:32,258 --> 00:10:34,545
Why don't we go somewhere

148
00:10:34,593 --> 00:10:39,178
a little closer first, say Cornwall,

149
00:10:39,223 --> 00:10:43,182
and we'll see how it goes.

150
00:10:43,227 --> 00:10:47,812
Right, of course, Cornwall.

151
00:10:47,898 --> 00:10:50,105
Hey, excuse me.

152
00:10:53,029 --> 00:10:57,148
Is this guy boring you?
Why don't you talk to me instead?

153
00:10:57,241 --> 00:11:00,108
I'm from a different planet.

154
00:11:03,205 --> 00:11:06,368
It's true. You want to see my spaceship?

155
00:11:07,877 --> 00:11:11,541
"Do you want to see my spaceship?"
What kind of chat-up line is that?

156
00:11:12,882 --> 00:11:14,793
That does happen.

157
00:11:14,884 --> 00:11:16,875
Speaking of...

158
00:11:17,928 --> 00:11:20,215
We've got two minutes.
Drink up.

159
00:11:20,931 --> 00:11:23,309
That's my house.

160
00:11:30,066 --> 00:11:34,105
People of Earth, a round of drinks,
for everyone, on me.

161
00:11:34,195 --> 00:11:36,903
You really think
the world's going to end?

162
00:11:36,947 --> 00:11:38,483
Yes.

163
00:11:39,367 --> 00:11:43,031
Shouldn't we lie down, or put a paper
bag over our heads, or something?

164
00:11:43,120 --> 00:11:46,078
- If you like.
- Will it help?

165
00:11:46,123 --> 00:11:48,831
Not at all.

166
00:11:48,918 --> 00:11:50,124
Last orders, then.

167
00:12:06,477 --> 00:12:08,809
- What is that?
- Run.

168
00:12:08,854 --> 00:12:10,811
Look out.

169
00:12:39,176 --> 00:12:40,837
Towel.

170
00:12:41,762 --> 00:12:43,753
Arthur.

171
00:12:43,848 --> 00:12:45,805
What the hell are those things?

172
00:12:46,725 --> 00:12:49,433
They're ships
from a Vogon constructor fleet.

173
00:12:49,520 --> 00:12:52,683
I picked up their signal this morning.
Here, you'll need this.

174
00:12:54,191 --> 00:12:57,309
- What are you doing?
- We're hitching a ride.

175
00:13:00,531 --> 00:13:05,025
People of Earth,
this is Prostetnic Vogon Jeltz

176
00:13:05,077 --> 00:13:07,694
of the Galactic Hyperspace
Planning Council.

177
00:13:07,746 --> 00:13:09,362
As you are probably aware,

178
00:13:09,415 --> 00:13:13,033
plans for the development
of the outlying regions of the galaxy

179
00:13:13,127 --> 00:13:17,667
involve the building of a hyperspace
express route through your star system.

180
00:13:17,756 --> 00:13:21,920
And your planet is one of those
scheduled for demolition.

181
00:13:29,977 --> 00:13:32,469
<i>There's no point
acting surprised about it.</i>

182
00:13:32,563 --> 00:13:35,055
<i>The plans have been on display</i>

183
00:13:35,191 --> 00:13:38,900
<i>at your local planning office
in Alpha Centauri for 50 Earth years.</i>

184
00:13:40,070 --> 00:13:43,779
<i>If you can't be bothered
with local affairs, that's your lookout.</i>

185
00:13:43,866 --> 00:13:46,324
Apathetic bloody planet.

186
00:13:46,410 --> 00:13:49,402
I've no sympathy at all.

187
00:15:36,854 --> 00:15:40,017
The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy

188
00:15:40,107 --> 00:15:42,098
<i>is a wholly remarkable book.</i>

189
00:15:42,192 --> 00:15:45,435
<i>Perhaps the most remarkable,
certainly the most successful,</i>

190
00:15:45,529 --> 00:15:49,614
<i>ever to come out of the great
publishing corporations of Ursa Minor.</i>

191
00:15:49,700 --> 00:15:52,988
More popular <i>than</i>
The Celestial Homecare Omnibus,

192
00:15:53,078 --> 00:15:56,867
<i>better selling than
53 More Things to Do in Zero Gravity,</i>

193
00:15:56,957 --> 00:15:59,949
<i>and more controversial than
Oolon Colluphid's trilogy</i>

194
00:16:00,044 --> 00:16:03,207
<i>of philosophical blockbusters,
Where God Went Wrong,</i>

195
00:16:03,297 --> 00:16:05,789
Some More of God's Greatest Mistakes,

196
00:16:05,883 --> 00:16:08,215
and Who ls This God Person Anyway?

197
00:16:09,053 --> 00:16:12,011
<i>It's already supplanted
the Encyclopaedia Galactica</i>

198
00:16:12,097 --> 00:16:15,055
<i>as the standard repository
of all knowledge and wisdom</i>

199
00:16:15,142 --> 00:16:17,725
<i>for two important reasons.</i>

200
00:16:17,811 --> 00:16:20,394
<i>First, it's slightly cheaper,</i>

201
00:16:20,522 --> 00:16:23,605
<i>and second, it has the words
"Don't Panic"</i>

202
00:16:23,692 --> 00:16:27,185
<i>printed in large,
friendly letters on its cover.</i>

203
00:16:35,788 --> 00:16:38,576
So you're not from Guildford?

204
00:16:38,749 --> 00:16:42,788
Which would explain the accent,
which I've always wondered about.

205
00:16:42,878 --> 00:16:46,667
You're not an out-of-work actor,

206
00:16:46,757 --> 00:16:52,218
but rather a writer for this...
this book thing.

207
00:16:53,013 --> 00:16:54,720
Good, huh?

208
00:16:54,765 --> 00:16:57,223
I don't feel well.
I need a cup of tea.

209
00:16:57,267 --> 00:17:00,680
If I asked where we were,
would I regret it?

210
00:17:00,771 --> 00:17:04,014
- We're safe for now.
- Good.

211
00:17:04,108 --> 00:17:07,942
We're in the washroom on one of the
ships of the Vogon constructor fleet.

212
00:17:08,070 --> 00:17:11,563
- Get me home, Ford.
- Arthur, your home is...

213
00:17:11,657 --> 00:17:16,242
Oh, God, my home.
My home was demolished.

214
00:17:21,125 --> 00:17:23,116
You don't remember.

215
00:17:24,086 --> 00:17:27,295
OK, Arthur, I've got
something to tell you.

216
00:17:27,381 --> 00:17:30,419
It's unfortunate, but it's true.

217
00:17:30,467 --> 00:17:33,676
Your home planet has been blown up.

218
00:17:42,521 --> 00:17:44,512
Blown up.

219
00:17:51,447 --> 00:17:53,438
Couldn't you have done something?

220
00:17:53,490 --> 00:17:57,529
I saved your life.
OK, that makes us even.

221
00:17:57,661 --> 00:18:00,995
It's a tough galaxy. If you want
to survive out here,

222
00:18:01,039 --> 00:18:05,283
you've gotta know where your towel is.

223
00:18:05,377 --> 00:18:07,914
OK, give me a hand over here.

224
00:18:10,340 --> 00:18:14,379
Careful. It's hot.
We've gotta get off this ship.

225
00:18:14,470 --> 00:18:16,552
<i>Before the Vegans find us.</i>

226
00:18:16,638 --> 00:18:19,676
Vogons, they hate hitchhikers. Pull.

227
00:18:25,481 --> 00:18:28,815
- Now we'll get a signal.
- What is a Vogon?

228
00:18:28,901 --> 00:18:30,733
Ask the Guide. Say "Vogons".

229
00:18:32,529 --> 00:18:34,566
Vogons.

230
00:18:35,365 --> 00:18:39,780
<i>Vogons are one of the
most unpleasant races in the galaxy.</i>

231
00:18:39,870 --> 00:18:44,205
<i>Not evil, but bad-tempered,
bureaucratic, officious and callous.</i>

232
00:18:44,249 --> 00:18:47,787
<i>They wouldn't even lift a finger
to save their own grandmothers</i>

233
00:18:47,878 --> 00:18:51,121
<i>from the Ravenous Bugblatter Beast
of Traal without orders</i>

234
00:18:51,215 --> 00:18:53,673
<i>signed in triplicate,
sent in, sent back,</i>

235
00:18:53,717 --> 00:18:57,051
<i>queried, lost, found,
subjected to public inquiry,</i>

236
00:18:57,221 --> 00:19:00,589
<i>lost again and finally buried
in soft peat for three months</i>

237
00:19:00,682 --> 00:19:03,515
<i>and recycled as firefighters.</i>

238
00:19:04,853 --> 00:19:09,643
<i>On no account should you allow
a Vogon to read poetry to you.</i>

239
00:19:11,276 --> 00:19:15,895
They can't think or imagine.
Most can't spell. They just run things.

240
00:19:22,204 --> 00:19:24,195
And if we don't get a ride soon,

241
00:19:24,289 --> 00:19:27,702
we won't need the Guide to tell us
how unpleasant the Vogons are.

242
00:19:27,751 --> 00:19:30,118
They've already destroyed
a planet today.

243
00:19:30,212 --> 00:19:32,544
That always makes them a little...

244
00:19:38,971 --> 00:19:41,929
- What is that?
- Put this in your ear.

245
00:19:46,478 --> 00:19:50,346
<i>We have unwittingly picked up
a couple of hitchhikers.</i>

246
00:19:50,440 --> 00:19:53,102
The fish is translating for you.

247
00:19:54,111 --> 00:19:57,229
<i>The Babel fish
is small, yellow, leech-like,</i>

248
00:19:57,281 --> 00:20:01,650
<i>and probably the oddest thing
in the universe.</i>

249
00:20:01,743 --> 00:20:06,203
<i>It feeds on brainwave energy,
absorbing unconscious frequencies,</i>

250
00:20:06,290 --> 00:20:08,827
<i>and excreting a matrix
of conscious frequencies</i>

251
00:20:08,959 --> 00:20:11,166
<i>to the speech centres of the brain.</i>

252
00:20:11,295 --> 00:20:14,788
<i>The practical upshot of which is that,
if you stick one in your ear,</i>

253
00:20:14,882 --> 00:20:20,468
<i>you instantly understand
anything said to you in any language.</i>

254
00:20:28,604 --> 00:20:31,062
Resistance is useless.

255
00:20:34,860 --> 00:20:36,976
- All right.
- Someone's coming.

256
00:20:37,070 --> 00:20:39,482
Here we go. Look lively.

257
00:21:16,902 --> 00:21:18,484
Sir.

258
00:21:18,528 --> 00:21:21,316
- What?
- Hitchhikers.

259
00:22:00,737 --> 00:22:03,946
"O freddled gruntbuggly..."

260
00:22:04,032 --> 00:22:06,569
No, really, you don't have to read.

261
00:22:06,702 --> 00:22:09,410
We've put you through
enough trouble already.

262
00:22:09,496 --> 00:22:14,616
"...as plerdled gabbleblotchits
on a lurgid bee."

263
00:22:14,710 --> 00:22:20,080
<i>Vogon poetry is widely accepted
as the third worst in the universe.</i>

264
00:22:21,258 --> 00:22:24,467
<i>The second worst
is that of the Azgoths of Kria.</i>

265
00:22:24,553 --> 00:22:28,091
<i>During a recitation by their
Poet Master, Grunthos the Flatulent,</i>

266
00:22:28,223 --> 00:22:31,090
of his poem
Ode to a Small Lump of Green Putty

267
00:22:31,226 --> 00:22:33,763
I Found in My Armpit
One Midsummer Morning,

268
00:22:33,937 --> 00:22:37,100
<i>four of his audience
died of internal haemorrhaging,</i>

269
00:22:37,232 --> 00:22:40,770
<i>and the president of the
Mid-Galactic Arts Nobbling Council</i>

270
00:22:40,861 --> 00:22:43,228
<i>survived by gnawing
one of his own legs off.</i>

271
00:22:43,280 --> 00:22:48,275
"Or I will rend thee
in the gobberwarts

272
00:22:48,326 --> 00:22:51,284
with my blurgle..."

273
00:22:51,371 --> 00:22:55,786
<i>The absolute worst poetry was
by Paula Millstone Jennings of Sussex.</i>

274
00:22:55,834 --> 00:22:58,371
<i>Luckily, it was destroyed
when the Earth was.</i>

275
00:22:58,462 --> 00:23:03,127
"See if I don't." Yeah.

276
00:23:05,302 --> 00:23:10,672
So, Earthlings,
I present you with a choice.

277
00:23:10,766 --> 00:23:13,929
Either die in the vacuum of space,

278
00:23:14,019 --> 00:23:18,809
or tell me what you thought of my poem.

279
00:23:20,442 --> 00:23:24,356
Actually, I rather liked it.

280
00:23:26,573 --> 00:23:29,281
That's good. Run with it.

281
00:23:29,367 --> 00:23:31,779
Some of the words I didn't understand,

282
00:23:31,870 --> 00:23:35,283
but I found the imagery quite effective.

283
00:23:36,166 --> 00:23:37,497
Continue.

284
00:23:37,584 --> 00:23:41,293
Well, yes,
interesting rhythmic devices,

285
00:23:41,338 --> 00:23:43,830
which seemed to counterpoint

286
00:23:43,882 --> 00:23:46,590
the underlying metaphor
of the humanity of...

287
00:23:46,676 --> 00:23:49,885
- Vogonity.
- Vogonity, sorry. Vogonity

288
00:23:49,971 --> 00:23:51,962
of the poet's soul.

289
00:23:56,019 --> 00:24:00,138
So what you're saying is,

290
00:24:00,190 --> 00:24:02,807
I write poetry because

291
00:24:02,901 --> 00:24:07,316
underneath this mean,
callous, heartless exterior,

292
00:24:07,364 --> 00:24:11,358
I just want to be loved?

293
00:24:12,661 --> 00:24:14,698
Yes.

294
00:24:14,746 --> 00:24:17,204
Yes, yeah, please.

295
00:24:22,838 --> 00:24:24,374
Throw them off the ship.

296
00:24:24,506 --> 00:24:27,874
- No.
- Ford.

297
00:24:29,553 --> 00:24:31,794
All right.

298
00:24:31,888 --> 00:24:35,426
Resistance is useless.

299
00:24:38,103 --> 00:24:42,643
Shut up. Get a job.
Wash your filthy hands.

300
00:24:42,732 --> 00:24:45,474
Don't panic.

301
00:24:45,569 --> 00:24:51,565
So this is it?
We're gonna die?

302
00:24:51,658 --> 00:24:55,242
Yeah, we're gonna die.

303
00:24:55,370 --> 00:24:58,283
No. No, what's this?

304
00:24:58,373 --> 00:24:59,989
What is this?

305
00:25:00,083 --> 00:25:04,418
What's this? This is nothing.
Yeah, we're gonna die.

306
00:25:15,098 --> 00:25:17,180
You're sweating.

307
00:25:25,442 --> 00:25:27,729
- Would you like a hug?
- No.

308
00:25:41,249 --> 00:25:44,833
<i>"Space," says the introduction
to The Hitchhiker's Guide,</i>

309
00:25:44,920 --> 00:25:47,412
<i>"is big. Really big."</i>

310
00:25:47,464 --> 00:25:52,880
<i>"You just won't believe how vastly,
hugely, mind-bogglingly big it is."</i>

311
00:25:52,969 --> 00:25:54,801
<i>And so on.</i>

312
00:25:54,930 --> 00:25:57,968
<i>It also says that
if you hold</i> a <i>lungful of air,</i>

313
00:25:58,099 --> 00:26:03,469
<i>you can survive in the total vacuum
of space for about 30 seconds.</i>

314
00:26:03,563 --> 00:26:05,770
<i>But with space being really big and all,</i>

315
00:26:05,857 --> 00:26:08,394
<i>the chances of being picked up
within that time</i>

316
00:26:08,485 --> 00:26:10,692
<i>are two to the power of two billion,</i>

317
00:26:10,779 --> 00:26:13,817
<i>79 million, 460 thousand,</i>

318
00:26:13,907 --> 00:26:16,865
<i>347 to one against.</i>

319
00:26:16,993 --> 00:26:18,734
<i>By a staggering coincidence,</i>

320
00:26:18,870 --> 00:26:21,487
<i>it's also the phone number
of the lslington flat</i>

321
00:26:21,581 --> 00:26:23,788
<i>where Arthur went to a fancy dress party</i>

322
00:26:23,875 --> 00:26:27,209
<i>and met a very nice young woman
whom he totally blew it with.</i>

323
00:26:30,715 --> 00:26:34,754
<i>Though the planet Earth,
the lslington flat and telephone</i>

324
00:26:34,844 --> 00:26:40,510
<i>have all now been demolished, Ford
and Arthur were, in fact, rescued.</i>

325
00:26:40,558 --> 00:26:43,391
- Ford?
- Yes.

326
00:26:43,478 --> 00:26:47,563
- I think I'm a sofa.
- I know how you feel.

327
00:26:55,031 --> 00:26:57,693
So much for the laws of physics.

328
00:26:57,826 --> 00:26:59,658
<i>And once again, our top story.</i>

329
00:26:59,703 --> 00:27:04,038
<i>The sensational theft of the most
coveted ship in the universe,</i>

330
00:27:04,124 --> 00:27:06,035
<i>the starship Heart of Gold.</i>

331
00:27:06,126 --> 00:27:08,663
<i>Stolen at the launch ceremony
by none other</i>

332
00:27:08,753 --> 00:27:11,586
<i>than Galactic President
Zaphod Beeblebrox.</i>

333
00:27:11,715 --> 00:27:16,960
<i>In the name of people, freedom,
and democracy, stuff like that,</i>

334
00:27:17,053 --> 00:27:21,138
<i>I hereby kidnap myself
and I'm taking the ship with me.</i>

335
00:27:21,224 --> 00:27:23,215
<i>Come on.</i>

336
00:27:23,310 --> 00:27:25,768
<i>Beeblebrox, universally considered</i>

337
00:27:25,854 --> 00:27:28,812
<i>to be the dimmest star
in several solar systems,</i>

338
00:27:28,940 --> 00:27:32,558
<i>is most famous for his controversial
defeat of Humma Kavula</i>

339
00:27:32,694 --> 00:27:36,653
<i>who claimed many thought they were
voting for the worst-dressed being</i>

340
00:27:36,740 --> 00:27:38,731
<i>in the universe contest.</i>

341
00:27:39,826 --> 00:27:40,907
Great.

342
00:27:40,952 --> 00:27:43,910
<i>Kavula is best remembered
for his slanderous</i>

343
00:27:43,997 --> 00:27:46,580
<i>"Don't Vote for Stupid!" campaign.</i>

344
00:27:46,624 --> 00:27:50,117
Put your ego aside.
Something important has happened.

345
00:27:50,211 --> 00:27:54,580
If there's anything more important than
my ego, I want it caught and shot now.

346
00:27:54,716 --> 00:27:56,423
Come on, I love it.

347
00:27:56,468 --> 00:27:59,506
<i>Zaphod's just this guy, you know.</i>

348
00:28:02,432 --> 00:28:03,422
What d'you...?

349
00:28:03,558 --> 00:28:07,802
- I was just watching myself.
- We have a couple of hitchhikers.

350
00:28:07,937 --> 00:28:10,474
Hitchhikers?
Why'd you pick up hitchhikers?

351
00:28:10,565 --> 00:28:12,431
I didn't. The ship did.

352
00:28:12,567 --> 00:28:14,808
What? Say what?

353
00:28:14,903 --> 00:28:19,522
When we engaged the
lmprobability Drive... The big button.

354
00:28:19,616 --> 00:28:21,357
- I know.
- They were picked up here,

355
00:28:21,451 --> 00:28:26,070
in sector ZZ9 Plural Z Alpha. Wait.
That's where you picked me up.

356
00:28:26,164 --> 00:28:28,121
- On Earth.
- That's impossible.

357
00:28:28,166 --> 00:28:31,500
- No, just very improbable.
- Listen. I don't have time for this.

358
00:28:31,628 --> 00:28:35,872
We've got the police of half the galaxy
after us. We've stopped for hitchhikers.

359
00:28:35,965 --> 00:28:38,343
So ten out of ten for style, but

360
00:28:38,426 --> 00:28:40,838
minus several million
for good thinking.

361
00:28:40,929 --> 00:28:44,217
You're too gorgeous, baby, stop it.
You drive me crazy.

362
00:28:45,308 --> 00:28:47,640
Don't. I'll send Marvin.

363
00:28:48,937 --> 00:28:50,644
Marvin.

364
00:28:53,817 --> 00:28:56,730
You ought to know,
I'm feeling very depressed.

365
00:28:57,862 --> 00:29:01,196
Well, we have something
that should take your mind off things.

366
00:29:01,282 --> 00:29:05,992
It won't work.
I have an exceptionally large mind.

367
00:29:06,079 --> 00:29:11,995
Yeah, we know. But we need you to go
down to the number two entry bay

368
00:29:12,127 --> 00:29:14,960
and pick up our stowaways
and bring them up here.

369
00:29:15,046 --> 00:29:18,334
Just that? I won't enjoy it.

370
00:29:18,466 --> 00:29:21,049
Yeah, well, that's life.

371
00:29:21,177 --> 00:29:25,421
Life? Don't talk to me about life.

372
00:29:34,607 --> 00:29:36,894
<i>- Commander Kwaltz.
- Yes.</i>

373
00:29:36,985 --> 00:29:41,479
<i>We have located the spaceship
Heart of Gold and President Beeblebrox.</i>

374
00:29:41,531 --> 00:29:45,741
<i>- Where'?
- Sector ZZ9 Plural Z Alpha.</i>

375
00:29:45,827 --> 00:29:48,319
<i>Requesting hyperspace clearance.</i>

376
00:29:48,413 --> 00:29:54,375
Hold your position, captain,
until clearance is granted.

377
00:29:54,419 --> 00:29:58,754
- Yes, sir.
- Get me Vice President Questular.

378
00:30:02,093 --> 00:30:06,382
<i>Hyperspace permission granted, captain.</i>

379
00:30:06,473 --> 00:30:08,805
Here we go.

380
00:30:30,413 --> 00:30:33,121
I think that door just sighed.

381
00:30:33,208 --> 00:30:35,666
Ghastly, isn't it?

382
00:30:35,752 --> 00:30:38,119
All the doors have been programmed

383
00:30:38,213 --> 00:30:41,422
to have a cheerful
and sunny disposition.

384
00:30:43,593 --> 00:30:48,429
Anyway, come on. I've been ordered
to take you up to the bridge.

385
00:30:50,266 --> 00:30:52,257
Please yourselves.

386
00:30:52,310 --> 00:30:55,553
Here I am,
brain the size of a planet,

387
00:30:55,605 --> 00:30:58,188
and they ask me to take you
up to the bridge.

388
00:30:58,316 --> 00:31:01,775
Call that job satisfaction?
Cos I don't.

389
00:31:01,903 --> 00:31:05,146
You can thank
the Sirius Cybernetics Corporation

390
00:31:05,240 --> 00:31:07,572
for building robots with GPP.

391
00:31:07,617 --> 00:31:11,155
- What's GPP?
- Genuine People Personalities.

392
00:31:11,287 --> 00:31:15,702
I'm a personality prototype.
You can tell, can't you?

393
00:31:21,839 --> 00:31:23,375
Arthur?

394
00:31:24,300 --> 00:31:28,885
<i>Hey, Slim, are you wearing
my underwear? Cos I'm wearing yours.</i>

395
00:31:28,972 --> 00:31:31,760
<i>And they ain't doing the trick.
Come on. All right.</i>

396
00:31:34,936 --> 00:31:36,973
Oh, for heaven's sake.

397
00:31:37,981 --> 00:31:40,848
I've brought the aliens.
Don't thank me or anything.

398
00:31:43,152 --> 00:31:45,189
Freeze.

399
00:31:45,321 --> 00:31:48,814
Freeze? I'm a robot. Not a refrigerator.

400
00:31:48,908 --> 00:31:52,492
- I wasn't talking to you, Giggles.
- Why do I bother?

401
00:31:52,620 --> 00:31:54,361
- Zaphod?
- Ford.

402
00:31:54,497 --> 00:31:58,912
Is that you? Ford. Praxibetel Ix.

403
00:31:59,002 --> 00:32:00,993
What the hell are you doing here?

404
00:32:01,087 --> 00:32:04,500
I just stuck out my thumb and here I am.

405
00:32:04,632 --> 00:32:07,420
- That is so you.
- Look at you.

406
00:32:07,552 --> 00:32:11,921
President of the Galaxy.
I can't believe you beat Humma Kavula.

407
00:32:12,015 --> 00:32:13,676
<i>You zarkin' flood.</i>

408
00:32:13,725 --> 00:32:18,140
I want you to meet a friend.
Arthur, this is Zaphod Beeblebrox.

409
00:32:19,355 --> 00:32:24,350
President of the Galaxy. This is
my cousin. He's a semi-half-brother...

410
00:32:24,402 --> 00:32:28,020
- We share three of the same mothers.
- We've met.

411
00:32:28,114 --> 00:32:33,575
Have we? I'm sorry.
I've got a terrible memory for species.

412
00:32:33,661 --> 00:32:37,996
This is him, Ford. The "would you
like to see my spaceship" bloke.

413
00:32:39,542 --> 00:32:44,833
- Hello, Arthur.
- Tricia.

414
00:32:44,881 --> 00:32:47,248
- How you doin'?
- Hey, Trillian.

415
00:32:47,383 --> 00:32:51,172
This is my semi-half-brother Ix,
I'm sorry, Ford.

416
00:32:51,220 --> 00:32:54,053
- Hi.
- Hi.

417
00:32:54,140 --> 00:32:58,134
Would you excuse us
for a second, please?

418
00:32:58,227 --> 00:33:01,436
You went down on that little planet
and didn't call me?

419
00:33:01,522 --> 00:33:04,389
Sorry, I didn't know.
I had a galaxy to run.

420
00:33:04,442 --> 00:33:06,729
Hi, Tricia McMillan, right?

421
00:33:06,819 --> 00:33:10,028
I think he called you Trillian.
Which of us got the right one?

422
00:33:10,073 --> 00:33:12,610
I shortened it
Something a little more spacey.

423
00:33:12,742 --> 00:33:15,325
Right. I was thinking
of changing mine to,

424
00:33:15,411 --> 00:33:17,402
I don't know, Arthoolia.

425
00:33:17,497 --> 00:33:21,491
That's a good one.
Well, this is weird.

426
00:33:21,584 --> 00:33:25,122
- How'd you get here?
- I just stuck out my thumb.

427
00:33:25,213 --> 00:33:28,831
- Right. In your pyjamas?
- I was in a hurry.

428
00:33:28,966 --> 00:33:31,048
OK. Did you know I was here?

429
00:33:31,094 --> 00:33:33,836
Don't flatter yourself.
I've got a spaceman too.

430
00:33:33,930 --> 00:33:36,592
Yeah, that's kinda like
the Dingo Shuffle, yeah.

431
00:33:36,724 --> 00:33:38,761
OK, look.

432
00:33:38,851 --> 00:33:42,685
I left you at the party. I feel bad, but
I was gonna call you when I got back.

433
00:33:42,814 --> 00:33:45,772
Well, there is no
going back now, is there?

434
00:33:46,901 --> 00:33:48,437
You do know what happened?

435
00:33:48,569 --> 00:33:51,357
Enough small talk.
We're on the run, remember?

436
00:33:51,447 --> 00:33:53,358
Excuse me, we're having a chat.

437
00:33:53,491 --> 00:33:55,949
Well, I think the girl's getting...
Boo.

438
00:33:56,035 --> 00:34:01,280
You blew it with her, Earthman, so shut
your face or I'll kick you in the zatch.

439
00:34:01,416 --> 00:34:02,998
- You wanna fight?
- OK.

440
00:34:03,126 --> 00:34:05,868
- No.
- I'm just kidding.

441
00:34:05,962 --> 00:34:09,375
I'm a kidder. Let's be friends.
Let's connect. You and I.

442
00:34:10,299 --> 00:34:12,210
Didn't see that one coming, did you?

443
00:34:12,301 --> 00:34:15,794
Popped right out of the box.
You foxy, yeah.

444
00:34:16,139 --> 00:34:19,348
Teach your pal a lesson, Ford.
He's a guest on my ship.

445
00:34:19,475 --> 00:34:21,807
He's a guest on my ship.

446
00:34:22,812 --> 00:34:24,849
I thought you said you stole it.

447
00:34:26,524 --> 00:34:29,391
Stole what?
What are we talking about?

448
00:34:31,028 --> 00:34:33,019
That doesn't sound good.

449
00:34:37,618 --> 00:34:40,986
- Are you OK?
- Just fabulous, thanks, Trill.

450
00:34:41,080 --> 00:34:43,822
A little help over here.
I'm in over my head.

451
00:34:43,958 --> 00:34:47,326
I'll take care of this. Good Zarquon,
do I have to do everything?

452
00:34:47,420 --> 00:34:48,660
Yes, I do.

453
00:34:48,755 --> 00:34:50,962
Hey, this is really pretty.

454
00:34:51,007 --> 00:34:53,590
- Don't.
- They're on our tail.

455
00:34:53,718 --> 00:34:56,050
Fire a gun. Launch a missile.
Do some damage.

456
00:35:05,605 --> 00:35:06,686
Stop that.

457
00:35:06,731 --> 00:35:08,768
Just kiddin'. I love it rough. Hit me.

458
00:35:08,858 --> 00:35:11,771
<i>- Computer'?
- Hi there.</i>

459
00:35:11,861 --> 00:35:13,943
